target_description: According to a May 16, 2018 CENTCOM press release, the U.S. conducted FOUR air strikes in Yemen in April 2018. CENTCOM accounted for two of those strikes on April 11 and April 23. This entry accounts for the SECOND of the TWO as-yet unnacounted for strikes, for which no known information regarding the specific strike is known. In the May 16 press release--which also referenced strikes conducted in February and March 2018--CENTCOM noted that "other air strikes took place in al Bayda, Hadramawt, Zamakh and Shabwah governorates." New America is not able to assign a month or date to any of these "other strikes," hence the date of this strike as April 1 is entirely arbitrary, and only accounts for the fact that the strike occured in April.

According to Al Masdar Online, two unidentified individuals were killed in an alleged drone strike in Baihan District.

A drone strike targeting a vehicle killed four people in Al Bayda' s Sawmah area on March 29th, according to reports by Anadolu and Xinhua. Anadolu reported that the strike killed three civilians naming one as Salim al-Manzari, a former head of Aden’s drivers union, while Xinhua reported that the strike killed three militants. A fourth individual died later in the hospital. Further reporting citing human rights advocates and family members of those killed assert they were civilians and not AQAP militants. U.S. Central Command denies civilians were killed in a March 29 statement, but on May 16, 2018 CENTCOM acknowledged reports of civilian casualties and said it had opened an assessment.

Stories from the Associated Press, which reported seven casualties, and Xinhua, which reported five casualties, cite Yemeni tribal leaders who said a U.S. drone strike targeted a house believed to be used by AQAP militants in Yemen's Ma'rib province on Thursday, March 22, 2018.
Per a June 6 press release to the Long War Journal, CENTCOM reported a strike on March 13, 2018 in Hadramawt. No information casualty figures or target type was provided.

target_description: According to local tribal sources interviewed by The Intercept, six civilians were killed in a drone strike targeting a car at around 5:00 PM that was carrying three adult sons of a local triba leader, Abdullah al-Qibli al-Wuhair, and three of his adult grandchildren, leaving an area previously hit by drone strikes. CENTCOM, per the Long War Journal, reported a strike on March 8 in Hadramawt. For the time being, New America is coding CENTCOM's March 8 strike here on March 9.

An Intercept report seemingly regarding the same strike said that one civilian child was killed in the strike. In a CENTCOM statement to the Long War Journal, this strike was recorded on March 5. As a result, New America has recoded this strike to March 5 from the original coding of March 6.

Given this divergent reporting, New America classifies--for now--all seven casualties as "Unknown." In an email to the Bureau of Investigative Journalism, CENTCOM denied conducting the strike. This will be updated if more information is released.

target_description: A U.S. drone strike in Yemen's Wadi Obeida district in Ma'rib province on Tuesday, December 19, 2017, killed two AQAP militants as they were traveling by vehicle. CENTCOM later announced the strike had killed Habib al-Sana'ni, whom it described as an AQAP weapons facilitator and intermediary to senior leaders.

A U.S. drone strike north of Wadi Obeida district in Yemen's Al Bayda' province on Friday, December 15th killed two AQAP militants as they were traveling by vehicle. CENTCOM later announced the strike had killed  Miqdad al Sana’ani, who was described as an AQAP external operations facilitator.

At least three Yemeni men, Fadl Tissi, Han Tissi and Sultan Amri, were killed in a U.S drone strike in Qaifa, a village in Bayda province.

Agence France-Presse reports those killed were ISIS militants, which would make this the second-ever U.S. drone strike targeting and killing ISIS militants in Yemen, the first of which occurred on October 16, 2017. Three to five AQAP militants died after what is believed to be a US drone fired on the vehicle in which they were traveling in Yemen's Al Bayda' province.
Two ISIS small munitions training camps were struck by 12 drone strikes on Oct. 16 in what reports are calling the first attack on the group in the country.

target_description: A vehicle carrying AQAP militants was targeted by a U.S. drone strike.

CENTCOM's press release reports that the raid, which they and other sources said included small-arms fire and precision airstrikes, killed seven AQAP militants and targeted "a series of buildings," according to Military Times. Reuters reports that the operation was a combination of U.S.-fired drone strikes followed by "automatic fire from low-flying helicopters," citing two local sources in Marib. The Intercept, Reuters and the New York Times report five civilian deaths. The DoD has not confirmed any civilian casualties. The raid was conducted to gather intelligence on AQAP, and was not in pursuit of any High Value Targets (HVTs). The New York Times reports that the Navy's SEAL Team 6 carried out the raid.
notes: Ground raid and drone strikes

target_description: Multiple reports list militant casualty numbers at 3, 4, and 5 and locations of the strike in Ma'rib and Shabwah governorates. The AFP reporting lists a precise village -- Rawda -- in Shabwah, while Al Jazeera and others primarily say the vehicle carrying the militants was in transit to Ma'rib to deliver weapons. Thus, we have entered the location for the strike in Shabwah.

Multiple individuals were killed in a U.S. drone strike on their vehicle in Shabwa province, according to Yemeni officials speaking on condition of anonymity. Initial reports were mixed as to whether there were three, four, or five militants in the vehicle at the time of the strike. Additional reporting by the Intercept referenced a Pentagon spokesperson acknowledging the deaths of "eight" AQAP terrorists but a local source, Ammar Salim Farid Alawlaqi, told the Intercept that none of the eight individuals killed -- including his uncle, Mansoor Allahwal Baras -- were active members of AQAP.though the Intercept's report acknowledged that those in the vehicle ha at least prior ties to militancy. Reuters reported the three not in the vehicle were civilians.

notes: U.S. forces conducted a strike April 18 in the Ma’rib governorate against three al-Qaida in the Arabian Peninsula terrorists

target_description: Two suspected Al Qaeda militants were struck while riding a motorbike in a U.S. drone attack on Saturday, according to unnamed officials speaking on condition of anonymity.

Nephew of slain AQAP leader Nasir Al-Wuhayshi, Khattab Al-Wuhayshi, was killed in an overnight strike on the town of Sawmaa in Baida province as he was riding a motorbike, a security official said on condition of anonymity.
A drone strike hit al Qaeda provincial official on Thursday night as he was riding a motorbike in southern Yemen.

The DoD-released statement on April 3, 2017 reported that the U.S. fired 20 strikes "targeting the sites of" AQAP in Yemen the weekend preceding, including "(AQAP) terrorists, as well as the terrorists’ infrastructure, fighting positions and equipment." Because New America cannot verify how many locations were targeted, at what times the strikes occurred, and on what days, the 20 strikes reported by the DoD will be included in this single entry. If more information is given that sheds light on the details New America needs to enter separate strikes, more entries will be added.
notes: precision airstrikes targeted al-Qaida in the Arabian Peninsula terrorists, as well as the terrorists’ infrastructure, fighting positions and equipment

target_description: Three suspected Al Qaeda militants were killed, to include a local leader of the group, Waddah Muhammed Amsouda. Amsouda was meeting others in a house at the time of the strike. Residents also reported a subsequent attack on a suspected Qaeda vehicle in Abyan province. However, casualties are unknown and these reports have not yet been corroborated.
A suspected U.S. drone strike killed at least four AQAP militants as they were traveling in their vehicle in Abyan province's Moudiya district.

U.S. drones killed two militants in a strike on a vehicle in southern Yemen on Monday, according to reports. According to Reuters, "Residents and tribal sources said a drone had fired a missile at a car traveling in Wadi Yashbum on Monday afternoon, destroying it completely." U.S. officials acknowledged the strike, but did not provide details.

Reuters reports that two civilian, non-AQAP affiliated brothers, Ahmed and Mohammed al-Khobze, both of whom were under the age of 15, were killed by a suspected U.S. drone strike while traveling in "an area in al-Bayda province where al Qaeda is known to operate."

Anadolu reports that Yasir Ali Abdallah al Silmi was killed by this strike on Monday, March 6, 2017. The New York Times reported that CAPT Jeff Davis, Pentagon spokesman, confirmed that Yasir Ali Abdallah al Silmi was killed in a strike on Thursday, March 2. That is where Yasir Ali Abdallah al Silmi's death is listed.

target_description: A U.S. military ground operation, authorized by President Donald J. Trump, was conducted in the Yakla district of Yemen's al-Bayda province on the morning of Sunday, January 29, 2017. According to CBS and other news outlets, the Navy's SEAL Team 6 carried out the attack that killed between 13 and 14 AQAP militants -- including potential female combatants, according to the Pentagon. Reports also claim that three AQAP leaders were killed. (AQAP has confirmed the death of Abdul-Raouf al-Dhahab.) The operation officially began Saturday evening around 9:00pm with, according to CBS, U.S. warplanes firing 16 missiles at three houses. U.S.-operated drones were also reportedly used. In addition to the AQAP militants, Yemeni officials say as many as 16 civilians -- including women and children -- were killed. This allegedly includes the eight-year-old daughter of deceased American cleric Anwar al-Awlaki, who was killed by a U.S. drone in Yemen in 2011. U.S. Central Command confirmed on March 9, 2017 that the operation caused between four and 12 casualties. A SEAL Team 6 operator, Chief Special Warfare Operator William "Ryan" Owens (USN), was killed during the operation. Three additional SEAL team members were wounded.

notes_1: Falsely reported to have killed Anwar Awlaki
notes:
The airstrikes were aimed at a large group of Qaeda operatives who had gathered in the southern province of Shabwa to plan attacks against the Yemeni government in retaliation for an offensive the week before, the Yemeni Embassy statement said.

\n

Yemeni officials said they had made targets of the leader of al-Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula, Nasser al-Wuhayshi, and his deputy, Said Ali al-Shihri, who were believed to be at the meeting with Mr. Awlaki. The Yemeni Embassy in Washington D.C. released a statement on December 24, 2009 saying, " "Today, Yemeni fighter jets launched an aerial assault at 4:30 a.m., on a remote location in the province of Shabwa." Other reports indicated that the strike was actually carried out by a U.S. cruise missile. The United States said it only provided intelligence, while Yemen denied involvement altogether. A diplomatic cable released by Wikileaks appears to indicate that it was indeed a U.S. strike, but it remains unclear what form the attack took.

notes: Six months after this strike took place, Amnesty International released images of U.S.-made cluster bombs that had purportedly been fired by American naval vessels during this attack.
